  "chunk_index": 26,
  "summary": "Officer Pierce informs Hakast that Ina Brent had approached him as people were leaving the trial, looking for the officer who provided evidence that day. Because Hakast was occupied with the county police commissioner, Pierce advised her to leave a message or return to the station. Ina had claimed her business was not important, though she appeared puzzled and remarked, \"I don't know if what she said is true.\" She was subsequently found strangled in a phone booth.\n\nHakast reflects on whether Ina's death was motivated by something she saw or heard regarding Hilary Webber's testimony. Hercule Poirot investigates the possibility that Ina went to Wilbraham Crescent to visit someone, considering three potential addresses: number 20 (Mrs. Blackham), number 19 (Miss Pembroke), and number 18 (Miss Watkins). Poirot notes that a knife, the suspected murder weapon, was found at number 20, and he wonders if Ina suspected Miss Pembroke of having a relationship with Hilary Webber or if Miss Watkins, who discovered the body, was involved.\n\nHakast calls Colin Lamb, who confirms he had lunch with Sheila Webb at a Chinese restaurant on Market Street at 1:00 PM following her shopping trip. This timeline contradicts the fact that Ina Brent died between 12:30 and 1:00 PM. Later, Poirot visits Miss Pembroke at 19 Wilbraham Crescent. She claims she was at home around 12:30 PM and denies that Ina Brent came to see her, expressing anger upon hearing of the murder.",
  "summary_whitespace_tokens": 240,
